as for the song, i think it's about how distant people can be from the world around them and current events. Sometimes reality seems like fiction. i have been told that the phrase "i'd love to turn you on" is a drug reference. "turning on" meant getting high back then i guess. John has said that the two events that inspired him to write the song were reading in the newspaper about Tara Browne's death and about plans to fill 4000 potholes in England. Now, of course that doesn't limit the meaning and it can be interpreted however. i mean, seriously, why would he write about potholes being filled if there wasn't something more to it? anyways just my two cents. i'll keep thinking about the song and maybe write something more later.
